Blocks.childText: HYMNS. 209 4 Because Thou art exceeding great, 4 Those that in wealth and pleasure live, And works by Thee are done Our daily groans deride Which are to be admired; and Thou And Thy delays of mercy give Art God Thyself alone. Fresh courage to their pride. 5 Teach me Thy way, and in Thy truth, 5 Our foes insult us, but our hope O Lord, then walk will I In Thy compassion lies, Unite my heart, that I Thy name This thought shall bear our spirits up, May fear continually. That God will not despise. 6 O Lord, my God, with all my heart Ps. 139 Second Part. To Thee I will give praise And I the glory will ascribe 1 IN all my vast concerns with Thee, Unto Thy name always. In vain my soul would try To shun Thy presence, Lord, or flee Ps. 119 Sixteenth Part. The notice of Thine eye. 1 My soul lies cleaving to the dust, 2 Thy all-surrounding sight surveys Lord, give me life divine My rising and my rest, From vain desires and every lust, My public walks, my private ways, Turn off these eyes of mine. And secrets of my breast. 2 When sore affictions press me down, 3 My thoughts lie open to the Lord, I need Thy quickening powers; Before they're formed within; Thy word, that I have rested on, And ere my lips pronounce the word, Shall help my heaviest hours. He knows the sense I mean. 3 Are not Thy mercies sovereign still, 4 O! wondrous knowledge, deep and high, And Thou a faithful God? Where can a creature hide Wilt Thou not grant me warmer zeal, Within Thy circling arms I lie, To run the heavenly road? Enclosed on every side. 4 Does not my heart Thy precepts love, 5 So let Thy grace surround me still, And long to see Thy face And like a bulwark prove, And yet how slow my spirits move, To guard my soul from every ill, Without enlivening grace! Secured by sovereign love. 5 Then shall I love Thy gospel more, H. 525 Death of a Youth. And ne'er forget Thy word, When I have felt its quickening power 1 WHEN blooming youth is snatched away To draw me near the Lord. By death's resistless hand, Our hearts the mournful tribute pay, Ps. 123 Which pity must demand. 1 O THOU, whose grace and justice reign 2 While pity prompts the rising sigh, Enthroned above the skies, O may this truth, impressed To Thee our hearts would tell their pain, With awful power, "I too must die," To Thee we lift our eyes. Sink deep in every breast. 2 As servants watch their master's hand, 3 Let this vain world delude no more; And fear the angry stroke; Behold the gaping tomb Or maids before their mistress stand, It bids us seize the present hour; And wait a peaceful look; To-morrow death may come. 3 So, for our sins, we justly feel 4 The voice of this alarming scene, Thy discipline, O God; Let every heart obey Yet wait the gracious moment still, Nor be the heavenly warning vain, Till Thou remove the rod. Which calls to watch and pray.
